would%20likely%20send%20me%20into%20early%20labor%20but%20said%20it%20would%20save%20my%20life.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThree%20days%20later%2C%20as%20I%20recovered%20in%20the%20intensive-care%20unit%2C%20my%20water%20broke%20at%209%3A15%20p.m.%20My%20baby%20was%20born%20by%209%3A50.%20When%20the%20nurse%20checked%20on%20me%20before%20that%2C%20I%20was%20fully%20dilated%20and%20the%20head%20was%20in%20the%20birth%20canal.%20My%20husband%20couldn't%20even%20make%20it%20to%20the%20hospital%20in%20time%2C%20though%20my%20doctor%20did.%20Later%2C%20I%20realized%20I%20likely%20hadn't%20noticed%20labor%20pains%20because%20I%20was%20on%20morphine%20after%20the%20colon%20surgery.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWe%20were%20expecting%20a%20daughter%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWe%20already%20had%20a%204-year-old%20daughter.%20After%20our%2020-week%20anatomy%20scan%2C%20we%20did%20a%20gender%20reveal.%20My%20niece%20opened%20the%20card%20and%20told%20us%20we%20were%20having%20another%20girl.%20We%20had%20no%20idea%20that%20the%20ultrasound%20tech%20had%20slipped%20wrong%20information%20into%20the%20card.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20Ryder%20was%20born%2C%20he%20cried%20for%20a%20minute%2C%20but%20his%20lungs%20were%20too%20underdeveloped%20to%20continue%20breathing.%20Doctors%20whisked%20him%20away%20to%20a%20ventilator.%20I%20didn't%20even%20get%20to%20look%20at%20the%20baby%2C%20who%20I%20believed%20was%20a%20second%20daughter.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELater%2C%20my%20doctor%20came%20to%20check%20on%20me%20and%20asked%20the%20baby's%20name.%20We%20told%20her%2C%20and%20she%20said%3A%20%26quot%3BThat's%20a%20funny%20name%20for%20a%20boy.%26quot%3B%20I%20was%20stunned.%20My%20mom%20was%20in%20the%20room%20with%20me%2C%20and%20she%20was%20so%20excited%20that%20she%20told%20my%20husband%20before%20I%20could.%20Amid%20a%20lot%20of%20trauma%2C%20finding%20out%20we%20had%20a%20son%20was%20a%20bright%20spot.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EI%20didn't%20see%20my%20baby%20for%203%20days%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20hospital%20where%20I%20delivered%20didn't%20have%20a%20neonatal%20intensive-care%20unit%2C%20so%20Ryder%20was%20transferred%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.chnola.org%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3EChildren's%20Hospital%20New%20Orleans%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%20I%20was%20still%20recovering%20from%20not%20only%20birth%20but%20also%20the%20colon%20removal.%20I%20hadn't%20been%20able%20to%20see%20my%20baby%2C%20but%20when%20the%20team%20stabilized%20him%20for%20transport%2C%20they%20wheeled%20him%20into%20my%20room%20in%20a%20big%20travel%20incubator.%20That%20was%20the%20first%20good%20look%20I%20got%20at%20my%20son%20%E2%80%94%20who%20still%20had%20no%20name.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20couldn't%20hold%20Ryder%20until%2077%20days%20after%20his%20birth.%20We%20were%20both%20fighting%20for%20our%20lives%2C%20and%20I%20had%20a%20whole%20new%20perspective.%20We%20had%20been%20devastated%20when%20our%20older%20daughter%20needed%20to%20spend%20one%20night%20in%20the%20hospital%20without%20us%20because%20she%20was%20jaundiced.%20But%20our%20son%20would%20spend%20nearly%20five%20months%20%E2%80%94%20or%20145%20days%20%E2%80%94%20in%20the%20NICU.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWe%20return%20to%20the%20NICU%20every%20year%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EToday%2C%20Ryder%20loves%20to%20act%2C%20sing%2C%20and%20play%20the%20piano.%20At%2010%2C%20his%20voice%20is%20full%20and%20beautiful.%20Hearing%20him%20sing%20is%20amazing%2C%20especially%20because%20his%20lungs%20were%20so%20weak%20at%20birth%20that%20he%20could%20barely%20cry.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEach%20year%20on%20Ryder's%20birthday%2C%20we%20return%20to%20the%20NICU%20that%20saved%20his%20life.%20They%20not%20only%20took%20care%20of%20Ryder%20but%20also%20helped%20our%20family%20heal.%20It's%20important%20to%20me%20that%20our%20family%20cares%20for%20the%20people%20who%20cared%20for%20us.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMany%20of%20the%20doctors%20and%20nurses%20who%20cared%20for%20Ryder%20have%20moved%20on%2C%20but%20the%20staff%20still%20know%20his%20story.%20He%20gets%20to%20hug%20the%2